Aug 22 2009 	Inscrutably worthwhile	The neighborhood in which this brand-new hotel is located is certainly a lively one: the starting point for low-fare out-of-town bus trips to Boston, Niagara Falls, etc.. In addition, the rich swirl of Chinatown is in all directions; just out the front door. In contrast, my clean-as-a-whistle guest room was a comfortable, 10th-floor hideaway of repose and tranquility, with a larger-than-usual room for New York City with king-sized bed, an ample bath, a large flat-screen TV, WiFi, an easy chair and a desk with office-type swivel chair. I was initially concerned about whether this hotel's location on the Lower East Side would interfere with my plans to visit other parts of Manhattan. But I found that its proximity to Canal Street, to public transit and walkability to Little Italy, Lower Broadway, St. Marks Place, etc. allayed most of my fears. Even parking was efficiently handled (for $30 overnight) a half-a-block away in a Chrystie St. garage. One downside: the single elevator can be a bit annoying. One hopes that management keeps it in good repair. This hotel is an amazing bargain in a city with few bargains. I would gladly return.	
