Aug 5 2009 	Great value off the beaten track	We just returned from an excellent stay at the Comfort Inn Manhattan Bridge in Manhattan's Chinatown. If you are willing to stay outside of midtown, this is certainly a good option. The price can't be beat ($104 a night, including a basic continental breakfast), the staff are pleasant, the hotel is brand new (and clean) and there are many interesting things to see within walking distance (Little Italy, Financial District, Soho, Ground Zero, Brooklyn Bridge, Staten Island Ferry, etc.) Don't be put off by the hotel being in Chinatown. Sure, the neighborhood is slightly chaotic, but the hotel itself is modern and quiet. When we wanted to go to midtown, we jumped on the subway for 2.50 each and were in Times Square in 4 or 5 stops. It was easy as pie. Otherwise it will be a 10-15$ cab ride.As for parking, there is a garage 1 block away that charges $30 a day. For $130 a day you have a clean and modern (...and compact) room, breakfast and parking. I don't think you can do much better than that.	
Jul 31 2009 	New and cheap in Chinatown	This is a new hotel just around the corner from Canal Street at the foot of the Manhattan Bridge. Basic accommodation with free breakfast and wi-fi. Small lobby with two computers for guest use. Some rooms probably have good views above the fifth or sixth floor. Situated across the street from a high school playground. Very active street during the day but becomes eerily quiet as Chinatown shuts down at night. Plan your food and drink accordingly. Easy access to several subway lines. We apparently threw their system into chaos when we tried to add an extra night to our existing reservation. We arrived to find that we had no reservation at all, despite being given not one, but two confirmation numbers, both of which showed as cancelled at check-in. I can only assume this was an isolated incident, along with the fire alarm that blared twice during our three-night stay at 9:30 and 3:30 in the morning, despite, thankfully, a lack of fire.Just to balance out these growing pains, we were given a spacious, wheelchair-accessible room that had a truly large bathroom, though I wondered why the bed, although very comfortable, sat so high off the floor in a room designed for physically-challenged guests.All we needed was a clean, comfortable and convenient place to sleep. At $104 before taxes per night AAA rate, this accommodation was an excellent value.	
